  <Subject Subject_ID="300266755">
    <Parent_Relationships>
      <Preferred_Parent>
        <Parent_Subject_ID>300000203</Parent_Subject_ID>
        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>complexes by function [300000203], complexes (buildings and sites) [300000202], Built Complexes and Districts (hierarchy name) [300000201], Built Environment (hierarchy name) [300264550], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>In general, areas or large, open structures used for burial or entombment. Specifically, typically refers to relatively large public parks or grounds laid out expressly for the interment of the dead, and not being the yard of any church. Originally the term was derived from the Latin "cœmeterium," referring to Roman underground cemeteries or catacombs.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000044883/National Park Service [online] (1998-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000114707/Oxford English Dictionary Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000042061/Webster's Third New International Dictionary (1961)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>In het algemeen, terreinen die worden gebruikt om overledenen te begraven of in tomben te plaatsen. Meer specifiek verwijst dit naar relatief grote openbare parken of terreinen die uitdrukkelijk voor teraardebestelling van doden bestemd zijn en die niet bij een kerk horen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>In der Regel verwendet um Areale für die Beerdigung oder Bestattung zu bezeichnen. Der Begriff bezieht sich  typischerweise auf relativ große, öffentliche Parkanlagen oder Flächen, die ausdrücklich für die Bestattung der Toten angelegt wurden und nicht auf die Bestattungsflächen rund um Kirchen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>一般而言，指用以埋葬或作為墳墓的區域。明確地說，通常指為埋葬死者所特別準備之較大型的公立園地或場地，且並非任何教堂的庭院。此詞彙本是由拉丁文 “cœmeterium”衍生而來，指羅馬人的地下墓穴。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
